<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Further </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">written evidence from Simon Creighton (LAI 0087)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1. During the oral evidence session, the Committee asked if we could provide written evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">about the responses made by the prison authorities to inquiries made by Members of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Parliament for their constituents (and also the possible impact of the proposed legal aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reforms on the work load of Members of Parliament). Unfortunately, we are not aware of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">any statistics specifically relating to prisoners that may assist the Committee and can only</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provide anecdotal feedback. However, we are aware of some general research concerning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the impact of legal aid cuts on MPs and their caseloads.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2. The right of prisoners to send confidential correspondence to MPs is not protected by the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Prison Rules 1999. The Rules only protect confidential correspondence with legal advisers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the courts.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> It is, however, prison service policy that correspondence between prisoners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and their MPs in relation to constituency business should be treated as confidential in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">same way as legally privileged communications.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This does not have any statutory footing.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“Correspondence between prisoners and their MP, AM and MEP must be treated as privileged but only where they are acting in a constituency capacity (not in a social capacity). This privilege does not extend to Members of the House of Lords, who have no constituency responsibilities, or to Local Councillors. All outgoing correspondence must be appropriately addressed i.e. to the particular Member at (i) the House of Commons, (ii) the National Assembly for Wales and (iii) the European Parliament and should also bear the prisoner’s home or current (prison) address.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> All</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">incoming correspondence should be written on and enclosed in officially recognised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stationery and displaying an official identifying mark of the appropriate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">authority. However, if an MP, AM or MEP is writing to a prisoner in a purely social</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">capacity, i.e. that individual is a personal friend or colleague, then the letter is not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">covered by this privilege and official stationery should not be used.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3. The Prison Service Instruction on the complaints process (PSI 2012/02) contains advice on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the right of prisoners to contact MPs in relation to the presentation of petitions but not in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">any other context:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“Every prisoner is entitled to petition Parliament. As a general rule, petitions to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Parliament are presented in the House of Commons; a prisoner who is not sure which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">House to petition should be advised to petition the House of Common </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">through a Member of Parliament</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The MP need not necessarily be the constituency MP of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">prisoner. Petitions may also be presented to the House of Lords via a member of that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">House.”</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (emphasis in original)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4. The terms of reference for the Parliamentary and Health Ombudsman, the body that may</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">review the work of the Prisons and Probations Ombudsman and deal with complaints arising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from the healthcare treatment of prisoners, requires a referral from the constituency MP.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5. Prior to the introduction of the complaints system in the early 1990s (following the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Woolf Report</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">), it was extremely common for prisoners to contact their MPs for assistance.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Anecdotally, our experience is that this is now far less common. We would, however, expect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">this to again become a routine method of complaint for prisoners and their families if access</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to legal advice is removed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6. In cases where MPs do raise issues for their constituents in custody, the general practice is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for a reply to be sent explaining the policy background and assuring the MP that the prisoner</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has been treated fairly and in accordance with that policy. We are not aware of any cases</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">where a substantive decision has been altered as a result of a MPs intervention.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Howard League’s focus on the wider policy issues as well as individual case work means that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">matters affecting individuals are often brought to the attention of MPs. While this is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">incredibly important in terms of advocating for systemic change, it has not proved an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effective means of achieve redress or justice for individuals on its own. In fact, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">involvement of MPs very often triggers a referral to a solicitor to provide legal advice and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">assistance.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">7. We are able to provide an example for the Committee. This concerned a question that arose</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">over the legality of the prison service’s policy barring all resettlement leaves for prisoners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">who had default terms for non payment of confiscation orders still to be served.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">following is an extract from the court documents lodged by one prisoner who had contacted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">her MP for assistance:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“The claimant also sought the assistance of her Member of Parliament, Sadiq Khan,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">who wrote on her behalf to the Ministry of Justice. On 17 September 2007 Maria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Eagle MP, Parliamentary Under Secretary of State responded to Mr Khan’s letter on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">behalf of the defendant. On the issue of the application of PSO 6300, she stated:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">—</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">‘Ms H is also concerned about her ability to maintain her family ties. Once a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">period in default for non-payment of a confiscation order is enforced, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">prisoner is immediately ineligible for [ROTL] on the original criminal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sentence; ROTL can only take place on the default term to serve providing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the period is [sic] default is of a reasonable length. Prison Service Order</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6300 Release on Temporary Licence (ROTL) was introduced in January 2006</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">following a lengthy consultation period. One of the key principles of ROTL is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to maintain public confidence in the administration of justice. Although Ms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">H’s case appears to be an extreme example, with such a small period to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">serve, there are many cases where the confiscation sum itself involves an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">extremely large amount of money and a lengthy term in default for non</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">payment. The current policy is designed to encourage prisoners to pay the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">proceeds of their crime.’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">She went on to explain that a post-implementation review of the PSO had begun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which had been delayed but would be completed at the earliest opportunity. Finally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">she expressed sympathy for the claimant.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On 25 February 2008 Maria Eagle responded to a further letter from Mr Khan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">explaining that the review had not been recommenced as planned due to other</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pressing priorities. She said that the Ministry would ensure that the review balances</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the needs of prisoners and their families as well as public confidence in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">administration of justice.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">8. In the event no review took place and a subsequent application for judicial review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">established that the policy was unlawful as it had placed a fetter on the discretion of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">prison Governor.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Had the prisoner not taken legal proceedings, the situation would not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">changed at all and the MP would simply have been assured that the system was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">operating properly.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">25 October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">See research by the Young Legal Aid Lawyers, available at </span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">http://www.younglegalaidlawyers.org/Nowhereelse-</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">to-turn-part2</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Prison Rules 1999, r 37</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">Prison Service Instruction 49/2011, paragraph 14.7</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Annex A</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> </span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">http://www.ombudsman.org.uk/make-a-complaint/how-to-complain </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">: “Please fill out a complaint form and pass it to an MP to refer your complaint to us. Having your complaint sent to us by an MP is a legal requirement.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Although we appreciate that this is not surprising as we would not be contacted in such cases.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Adesola Adelana v The Governor of HMP Downview, Secretary of State for Justice [2008] EWHC 2612 (Admin)</span></p></body></html>